article.headline: Catchings, Williams pace Indiana's victory
article.linkText: Indiana, N.Y., Cleveland tied for fourth playoff spot
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- For the second consecutive year, the Indiana
Fever are cutting it close in the WNBA playoff race.

Indiana made the playoffs for the first time in its three-year
history last season by defeating Cleveland in its final game.

On Saturday night, they had to beat Cleveland to stay alive and
set the stage for a Monday night showdown against Connecticut in
the season finale for both teams.

Natalie Williams had 15 points and 11 rebounds, the 61st
double-double of her WNBA career, as the Fever kept their playoff
hopes alive by beating the Cleveland Rockers 59-46.

Tamika Catchings, the league's third-leading scorer and
sixth-leading rebounder, overcame an eye injury to contribute 15
points.

Indiana and Cleveland are tied with New York for the final
playoff spot in the tight Eastern Conference, where only Detroit
has clinched a playoff spot.

Charlotte is second at 17-15. Connecticut is third at 17-16.
Cleveland, Indiana and New York are 16-17. The Liberty play at
Charlotte on Sunday, while Indiana hosts Connecticut, and Cleveland
hosts Charlotte on Monday, the regular season's final day.

Catchings caught an inadvertent elbow from LaToya Thomas with
4:13 remaining in the first half, suffering a cut to the left eye
that required three stitches. Indiana was leading 25-19 when
Catchings was hurt, and the Fever was still ahead, 34-26, when she
returned wearing a bandage below her eye with 14:30 to play.

"I got caught with the elbow. I lost a contact, and I knew I
probably had to have stitches," Catchings said.

But, it was the defense that made the difference as Cleveland
missed all nine of its 3-point attempts and was outscored 36-22 in
the paint.

"We've been focusing on defense," Catchings said. "We didn't
expect to be in this scenario at this point in the season. But,
when it comes down to crunch time. Nell has prepared us."

Williams agreed.

"The defense really came through for us, despite having tired
legs from last night's game," she said. "The main focus was
stopping the post players. In previous games, Cleveland post
players had made a high percentage of their shots."

The Fever took the lead for good at 14-11 on a 3-pointer by
Catchings. They built it to 10 before going six minutes without
scoring as the Rockers, who had defeated Indiana in three previous
games this season, pulled within three.

The Fever responded by scoring the final two points of the first
half and the first five points of the second to lead 32-22. The
Rockers, who shot just 33 percent from the field, never drew closer
than eight points again.

"Our adrenaline is flowing. We know what we need to do," said
Indiana coach Nell Fortner, who saw her team win six of its final
seven games last year to reach the playoffs. "Monday it's win or
go home. No motivational speeches are needed. ... Our backs are
against the wall. There is no room for error."

Christy Melvin led Cleveland with 12 points and Thomas scored
11. Kristen Rasmussen scored 11 for Indiana.
